[{"location":"included_site_types/#SiteTypes-included-in-this-package","page":"New site types","title":"SiteTypes included in this package","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"This package extends the SiteType collection provided by ITensor, by defining types for (vectorized) density matrices associated to built-in and operators acting on them.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"For each of these site types, each operator from the \"original\", non-vectorized ITensor site type is promoted as a pre- or post-multiplication operator. In other words, if there exists an operator \"A\" for the \"Fermion\" type, then you will find operators \"A⋅\" and \"⋅A\" (the dot here is a \\cdot) available for the \"vFermion\" site type.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Moreover, the gkslcommutator function allows you to easily define the unitary term (the commutator) in the GKSL equation: given a list of operator names and site indices, it returns an OpSum object representing the xmapsto -iAx map, for example","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"julia> gkslcommutator(\"A\", 1)\nsum(\n  0.0 - 1.0im A⋅(1,)\n  0.0 + 1.0im ⋅A(1,)\n)\n\njulia> gkslcommutator(\"A\", 1, \"B\", 3)\nsum(\n  0.0 - 1.0im A⋅(1,) B⋅(3,)\n  0.0 + 1.0im ⋅A(1,) ⋅B(3,)\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Operators are also vectorized, with the aim of computing expectation values: if a_i_i=1^d and r_i_i=1^d are, respectively, the coordinates of the operator A and the state rho with respect to the Gell-Mann basis, then the expectation value operatornametr(rho A) is given by sum_i=1^doverlinea_ir_i. Below you can find some operators transformed this way: they are actually \"states\" in the ITensor formalism, even if they represent operators. Their operator names are usually obtained by prefixing a v to the original ITensor name.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vS1/2\"-SiteType","page":"New site types","title":"\"vS=1/2\" SiteType","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Site indices with the \"vS=1/2\" site type represent the density matrix of a S=12 spin, namely its coefficients with respect to the basis of 2x2 Gell-Mann matrices.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Making a single \"vS=1/2\" site or collection of N \"vS=1/2\" sites","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"s = siteind(\"vS=1/2\")\nsites = siteinds(\"vS=1/2\", N)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vS1/2\"-states","page":"New site types","title":"\"vS=1/2\" states","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"The available state names for \"vS=1/2\" sites are:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"Up\" spin in the uparrowranglelangleuparrow state\n\"Dn\" spin in the downarrowranglelangledownarrow state","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vS1/2\"-vectorized-operators","page":"New site types","title":"\"vS=1/2\" vectorized operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Vectorized operators or associated with \"vS=1/2\" sites can be made using the state function, for example","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Sx4 = state(\"vSx\", s, 4)\nN3 = state(\"vN\", sites[3])","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Spin operators:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"vId\" Identity operator I_2\n\"vσx\" Pauli x matrix sigma^x\n\"vσy\" Pauli y matrix sigma^y\n\"vσz\" Pauli z matrix sigma^z\n\"vSx\" Spin x operator S^x = frac12 sigma_x\n\"vSy\" Spin y operator S^y = frac12 sigma_y\n\"vSz\" Spin z operator S^z = frac12 sigma_z\n\"vN\" Number operator N = frac12 (I_2+sigma_z)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"Osc\"-SiteType","page":"New site types","title":"\"Osc\" SiteType","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"A SiteType representing a harmonic oscillator. It inherits definitions from the \"Qudit\" type.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Available keyword arguments for customization:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"dim (default: 2): dimension of the index (number of oscillator levels)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"For example:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"sites = siteinds(\"Osc\", N; dm=3)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vOsc\"-Operators","page":"New site types","title":"\"vOsc\" Operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Operators associated with \"Osc\" sites:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Single-oscillator operators:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"A\" (aliases: \"a\") annihilation operator\n\"Adag\" (aliases: \"adag\", \"a†\") creation operator\n\"Asum\" equal to a+a^dagger\n\"X\" equal to frac1sqrt2(a^dagger+a)\n\"Y\" equal to fracisqrt2(a^dagger-a)\n\"N\" (aliases: \"n\") number operator","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vOsc\"-SiteType","page":"New site types","title":"\"vOsc\" SiteType","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Available keyword arguments for customization:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"dim (default: 2): dimension of the index (number of oscillator levels)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"For example:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"sites = siteinds(\"vOsc\", N; dim=4)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vOsc\"-states","page":"New site types","title":"\"vOsc\" states","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"States associated with \"vOsc\" sites.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"n\", where n is an integer between 0 and dim-1, gives the Fock state nranglelangle n\n\"ThermEq\", with additional parameters temperature and frequency, gives the thermal equilibrium (Gibbs) state ``\\operatorname{tr}(\\exp(-\\frac{\\omega}{T}","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"N))\\exp(-\\frac{\\omega}{T} N)``","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"X⋅ThermEq\", with additional parameters temperature and frequency, gives the thermal equilibrium state (as in the previous point) multiplied by X=frac1sqrt2(a^dagger+a) on the left (this is not actually a state, but it is useful when computing the correlation function of the X operator)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Example:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"s = siteind(\"vOsc\", N; dim=4)\nrho_eq = state(\"ThermEq\", s; temperature=1.0, frequency=5.0)\nfock_st = state(\"3\", s)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vOsc\"-Operators-2","page":"New site types","title":"\"vOsc\" Operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Vectorized operators associated with \"vOsc\" sites.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Single-oscillator operators (see the operator for \"Osc\" sites for their meaning):","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"vA\"\n\"vAdag\"\n\"vN\"\n\"vX\"\n\"vY\"\n\"vId\"","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vFermion\"-SiteType","page":"New site types","title":"\"vFermion\" SiteType","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Site indices with the \"vFermion\" SiteType represent spinless fermion sites with the states 0rangle, 1rangle, corresponding to zero fermions or one fermion.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vFermion\"-states","page":"New site types","title":"\"vFermion\" states","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"The available state names for \"vFermion\" sites are:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"Emp\" unoccupied fermion site\n\"Occ\" occupied fermion site","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vFermion\"-operators","page":"New site types","title":"\"vFermion\" operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Vectorized operators associated with \"vFermion\" sites:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"vId\" Identity operator\n\"vN\" Density operator\n\"vA\" (aliases: \"va\") Fermion annihilation operator\n\"vAdag\" (aliases: \"vadag\", \"vA†\", \"va†\") Fermion creation operator","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Note that these creation and annihilation operators do not include Jordan-Wigner strings.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vElectron\"-SiteType","page":"New site types","title":"\"vElectron\" SiteType","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"The states of site indices with the \"vElectron\" SiteType correspond to 0rangle, uparrowrangle, downarrowrangle, uparrowdownarrowrangle.","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vElectron\"-states","page":"New site types","title":"\"vElectron\" states","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"The available state names for \"vElectron\" sites are:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"Emp\" unoccupied electron site\n\"Up\" electron site occupied with one up electron\n\"Dn\" electron site occupied with one down electron\n\"UpDn\" electron site occupied with two electrons (one up, one down)","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/#\"vElectron\"-operators","page":"New site types","title":"\"vElectron\" operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"Vectorized operators associated with \"vElectron\" sites:","category":"page"},{"location":"included_site_types/","page":"New site types","title":"New site types","text":"\"vId\" Identity operator\n\"vNtot\" Total density operator\n\"vNup\" Up density operator\n\"vNdn\" Down density operator\n\"vNupNdn\" Product of n↑ and n↓","category":"page"},{"location":"#LindbladVectorizedTensors.jl","page":"Home","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for LindbladVectorizedTensors.","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/#GKSL-equation","page":"Examples","title":"GKSL equation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"With the states and operators defined by this package, we can define a Lindbladian operator acting on density matrices in a GKSL equation. Let's take, as an example, a system of N=3 harmonic oscillators described by the Hamiltonian","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"H=\nsum_j=1^Nomega_j a^dagger_j a_j + \nsum_j=1^N-1lambda_j (a^dagger_j a_j+1 + a^dagger_j+1 a_j)","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"and where each oscillator is damped according to the dissipator operator","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"mathcalD(rho)=\nsum_j=1^N gamma_j bigl( a_j rho a^dagger_j - tfrac12 rho a^dagger_j a_j -\ntfrac12 a^dagger_j a_j rho bigr)","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"First, create the site indices. In this example, we will use an arbitrary value for the number of levels of the oscillators:","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"N = 3\ns = siteinds(\"vOsc\", 3; dim=5)","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Create the OpSum object representing the unitary part of the evolution, -iH-:","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"ℓ = OpSum()\nfor j in 1:N\n    ℓ += ω[j] * gkslcommutator(\"N\", j)\nend\nfor j in 1:(N - 1)\n    ℓ +=\n        λ[j] * (\n            gkslcommutator(\"Adag\", site1, \"A\", site2) +\n            gkslcommutator(\"A\", site1, \"Adag\", site2)\n        )\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Finally, add the dissipator:","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"for j in 1:N\n    ℓ += γ, \"A⋅ * ⋅Adag\", n\n    ℓ += -γ / 2, \"N⋅\", n\n    ℓ += -γ / 2, \"⋅N\", n\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"This OpSum object can now, for example, be cast into an MPO and used to evolve a state with the TDVP algorithm. Here is how L can be applied to a state ρ:","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"ρ = MPS([state(\"ThermEq\", s[j]; temperature=1.0, frequency=5.0) for j in 1:N])\nL = MPO(ℓ, s)\napply(L, ρ)","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"Computing the expectation value of an operator A on a state ρ means computing operatornametr(Aρ): with this package, this is done by contracting the ITensor state representing the adjoint of the vectorized operator with the ITensor state representing ρ. For example, if A is the number operator on site 3, i.e Iotimes Iotimes N, then we need the following code.","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"vec_n = MPS(s, [i == 3 ? \"vN\" : \"vId\" for i in 1:N])\nresult = dot(vec_n, ρ)","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"As a particular case, the trace of the state can be obtained by \"measuring\" the identity operator:","category":"page"},{"location":"gksl_example/","page":"Examples","title":"Examples","text":"vec_id = MPS(s, \"vId\")\ntrace = dot(vec_id, ρ)","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#Physical-operators","page":"Reference","title":"Physical operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"physical_operators/#Spin-chain-operators","page":"Reference","title":"Spin chain operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"physical_operators/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"exchange_interaction\nexchange_interaction_adjoint\nexchange_interaction′\nspin_chain\nspin_chain_adjoint\nspin_chain′","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.exchange_interaction","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.exchange_interaction","text":"exchange_interaction(s1::Index, s2::Index; kwargs...)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the Hamiltonian part -iH  of an exchange interaction between sites s1 and s2 term in a GKSL equation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.exchange_interaction_adjoint","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.exchange_interaction_adjoint","text":"exchange_interaction_adjoint(s1::Index, s2::Index; kwargs...)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the adjoint of the Hamiltonian part -iH  of an exchange interaction between sites s1 and s2 term in a GKSL equation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.exchange_interaction′","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.exchange_interaction′","text":"exchange_interaction_adjoint(s1::Index, s2::Index; kwargs...)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the adjoint of the Hamiltonian part -iH  of an exchange interaction between sites s1 and s2 term in a GKSL equation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.spin_chain","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.spin_chain","text":"spin_chain(\n    freqs::Vector{<:Real},\n    coups::Vector{<:Real},\n    sites::Vector{<:Index}\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the Hamiltonian part -iH  of the GKSL equation for a spin chain of frequencies freqs and coupling constants coups, on sites.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.spin_chain_adjoint","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.spin_chain_adjoint","text":"spin_chain_adjoint(\n    freqs::Vector{<:Real},\n    coups::Vector{<:Real},\n    sites::Vector{<:Index}\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the adjoint of the Hamiltonian part -iH  of the GKSL equation for a spin chain of frequencies freqs and coupling constants coups, on sites.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.spin_chain′","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.spin_chain′","text":"spin_chain_adjoint(\n    freqs::Vector{<:Real},\n    coups::Vector{<:Real},\n    sites::Vector{<:Index}\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the adjoint of the Hamiltonian part -iH  of the GKSL equation for a spin chain of frequencies freqs and coupling constants coups, on sites.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#Pseudomode-operators","page":"Reference","title":"Pseudomode operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"physical_operators/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"dissipator_loss\ndissipator_gain\ndissipator\nmixedlindbladplus\nmixedlindbladminus","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.dissipator_loss","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.dissipator_loss","text":"dissipator_loss(n::Int)\n\nReturn an OpSum object representing a dissipator operator (as in a GKSL equation) on site n, associated to the jump operator A (the annihilation operator). The OpNames A and Adag must be defined for the site type in use.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.dissipator_gain","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.dissipator_gain","text":"dissipator_gain(n::Int)\n\nReturn an OpSum object representing a dissipator operator (as in a GKSL equation) on site n, associated to the jump operator Adag (the creation operator). The OpNames A and Adag must be defined for the site type in use.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.dissipator","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.dissipator","text":"dissipator(n::Int, frequency::Real, temperature::Real)\n\nReturn an OpSum object which represents the dissipator in the GKSL equation for given frequency and temperature, i.e. with dissipation coefficient 1/(exp(freq/temp) - 1).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.mixedlindbladplus","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.mixedlindbladplus","text":"mixedlindbladplus(n1::Int, n2::Int)\n\nReturn on OpSum expression which represents a mixed dissipation operator, appearing in the equation for two pseudomodes, on sites at positions n1 and n2 in the system.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.mixedlindbladminus","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.mixedlindbladminus","text":"mixedlindbladminus(n1::Int, n2::Int)\n\nReturn on OpSum expression which represents a mixed dissipation operator, appearing in the equation for two pseudomodes, on sites at positions n1 and n2 in the system.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#Markovian-closure-operators","page":"Reference","title":"Markovian closure operators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"physical_operators/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"Closure","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.Closure","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.Closure","text":"A Closure object stores the parameters that define a Markovian closure, providing different ways to input them.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"physical_operators/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"closure","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure","text":"closure(\n    Ω::Real, K::Real,\n    α::Matrix{<:Real}, β::Matrix{<:Real}, w::Matrix{<:Real}\n)\n\nConstruct a Closure object with asymptotic frequency Ω and coupling K, with the universal parameter set given by α, β and w, each of which is assumed to be a two-column matrix with the real parts of the parameters in the first column and the imaginary parts in the second one.\n\n\n\n\n\nclosure(\n    Ω::Real, K::Real,\n    α::Vector{<:Complex}, β::Vector{<:Complex}, w::Vector{<:Complex}\n)\n\nConstruct a Closure object with asymptotic frequency Ω and coupling K, with the universal parameter set given by α, β and w, which are assumed to be vectors of complex numbers.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"length(mc::Closure)\nfreqs(mc::Closure)\ninnercoups(mc::Closure)\noutercoups(mc::Closure)\ndamps(mc::Closure)\nfreq(mc::Closure, j::Int)\ninnercoup(mc::Closure, j::Int)\noutercoup(mc::Closure, j::Int)\ndamp(mc::Closure, j::Int)","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#Base.length-Tuple{Closure}","page":"Reference","title":"Base.length","text":"length(mc::Closure)\n\nReturn the length of a Markovian closure, i.e. the number of pseudomodes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.freqs-Tuple{Closure}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.freqs","text":"freqs(mc::Closure)\n\nReturn the list of frequencies of the pseudomodes in the given Markovian closure.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.innercoups-Tuple{Closure}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.innercoups","text":"innercoups(mc::Closure)\n\nReturn the list of inner couplings of the pseudomodes in the Markovian closure mc, i.e. the coupling constant between the pseudomodes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.outercoups-Tuple{Closure}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.outercoups","text":"outercoups(mc::Closure)\n\nReturn the list of outer couplings of the pseudomodes in the Markovian closure mc, i.e. the coupling constants with the last point of the TEDOPA chain.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.damps-Tuple{Closure}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.damps","text":"damps(mc::Closure)\n\nReturn the list of damping coefficients of the pseudomodes in the Markovian closure mc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.freq-Tuple{Closure, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.freq","text":"freq(mc::Closure, j::Int)\n\nReturn the frequency of the j-th pseudomode of the Markovian closure mc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.innercoup-Tuple{Closure, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.innercoup","text":"innercoup(mc::Closure, j::Int)\n\nReturn the coupling coefficient between the j-th and the j+1-th pseudomodes of the Markovian closure mc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.outercoup-Tuple{Closure, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.outercoup","text":"outercoup(mc::Closure, j::Int)\n\nReturn the coupling coefficient of the j-th pseudomode in the Markovian closure mc, with the last point of the TEDOPA chain.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.damp-Tuple{Closure, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.damp","text":"damp(mc::Closure, j::Int)\n\nReturn the damping coefficient of the j-th pseudomode in the Markovian closure mc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"closure_op(mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int)\nclosure_op_adjoint(\n    mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int, gradefactor::Int\n)\nclosure_op′\nfilled_closure_op\nfilled_closure_op_adjoint\nfilled_closure_op′","category":"page"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure_op-Tuple{Closure, Vector{<:Index}, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure_op","text":"closure_op(mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the Markovian closure operators with parameters given by mc, on sites sites, linked to the main TEDOPA/thermofield chain on site chain_edge_site. This closure replaces a chain starting from an empty state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure_op_adjoint-Tuple{Closure, Vector{<:Index}, Int64, Int64}","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure_op_adjoint","text":"closure_op_adjoint(\n    mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int, gradefactor::Int\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the adjoint of the Markovian closure operators with parameters given by mc, on sites sites, linked to the main TEDOPA/thermofield chain on site chain_edge_site. The integer gradefactor is the parity (1: even, -1: odd) of the operator subject to the time evolution. This closure replaces a chain starting from an empty state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure_op′","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.closure_op′","text":"closure_op_adjoint(\n    mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int, gradefactor::Int\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the adjoint of the Markovian closure operators with parameters given by mc, on sites sites, linked to the main TEDOPA/thermofield chain on site chain_edge_site. The integer gradefactor is the parity (1: even, -1: odd) of the operator subject to the time evolution. This closure replaces a chain starting from an empty state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.filled_closure_op","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.filled_closure_op","text":"filled_closure_op(mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the Markovian closure operators with parameters given by mc, on sites sites, linked to the main TEDOPA/thermofield chain on site chain_edge_site. This closure replaces a chain starting from a completely filled state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.filled_closure_op_adjoint","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.filled_closure_op_adjoint","text":"filled_closure_op_adjoint(\n    mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int, gradefactor::Int\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the Markovian closure operators with parameters given by mc, on sites sites, linked to the main TEDOPA/thermofield chain on site chain_edge_site. The integer gradefactor is the parity (1: even, -1: odd) of the operator subject to the time evolution. This closure replaces a chain starting from a completely filled state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"physical_operators/#LindbladVectorizedTensors.filled_closure_op′","page":"Reference","title":"LindbladVectorizedTensors.filled_closure_op′","text":"filled_closure_op_adjoint(\n    mc::Closure, sites::Vector{<:Index}, chain_edge_site::Int, gradefactor::Int\n)\n\nReturn an OpSum object encoding the Markovian closure operators with parameters given by mc, on sites sites, linked to the main TEDOPA/thermofield chain on site chain_edge_site. The integer gradefactor is the parity (1: even, -1: odd) of the operator subject to the time evolution. This closure replaces a chain starting from a completely filled state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"}]
